“We’re still expecting Kemsa to give us our ventilators. Dr Iscar Oluoch being part of this team should help us locate the ventilators,” Mr Obado said, adding that the county would not be lagging behind if all the ventilators were brought to the facility.
Kemsa is entangled in a multi-million scandal involving illegal procurement of Covid-19-related supplies.
Col Nyamita and Mr Oyugi, in an interview with the Nation at Migori Referral Hospital, confirmed that the county procured four ventilators earlier in the year before receiving four others from USAid a fortnight ago, while two others and the CPAP were supplied by Kemsa on December 22.
“I want to be categorical that of all the equipment in our possession, none is missing. There is a misconception going round, which was occasioned by four other equipment from the World Bank that are yet to be delivered,” Mr Oyugi said. Lobby piles pressure on the government, noting investigations into the Kemsa scandal and others are still incomplete. The 6.1-tonne consignment of pentavalent vaccine arrived in 2017 and expired the following year due to clearance issues. The new year has a rude welcome in the end of the Covid-19 tax reliefs. Without fees during the nine-month closure, many private schools were unable to pay staff, teachers and other workers. Senator speaks about a meeting that saved Nairobi, his governorship candidature and more.